// LC Economics Walkthroughs Data (auto-generated)
var WALKTHROUGHS_ECONOMICS = {
  "2022": [
    // ===== SECTION A: Short Response Questions (75 marks) =====
    {num:1, label:"Q1: Price Elasticity of Demand",
     q:"(a) Using an appropriate formula, calculate the price elasticity of demand depicted in the graph where the original price of the packet of face masks is \u20ac4 and then increases to \u20ac5. Show all calculations.\n\n(b) With reference to the graph above explain the law of demand.",
     a:"(a) Formula: (Change in Qd / Change in P) x (P1 + P2) / (Qd1 + Qd2)\n= (-4 / +1) x (4 + 5) / (8 + 4)\n= -4 x 9/12\n= -3\nThe PED is -3, meaning demand is price elastic.\n\n(b) The Law of Demand states that as the price of a good or service increases, the quantity demanded of that good or service decreases, and vice versa (ceteris paribus). This can be seen in the graph: as price increases from \u20ac4 to \u20ac5, quantity demanded decreases from 8 to 4 units."},

    {num:2, label:"Q2: Balance of Payments & National Accounts",
     q:"The infographic shows the Quarterly National Accounts for Quarter 2, 2021.\n\n(a) Using the data, explain whether the Balance of Payments is likely to have an overall expansionary or contractionary effect. Refer to relevant figures.\n\n(b) Outline one factor which could have influenced the trend in Personal Consumption in Quarter 2, 2021.",
     a:"(a) Expansionary.\nExports have increased by 6.4% and imports have increased by 5.4%. The increase in exports is 1% larger than the increase in imports, thus the injections are larger than leakages, which will have an overall expansionary effect on the economy.\n\n(b) Possible factors:\n- Pent up demand: consumers couldn't spend during lockdowns.\n- Increases in income: employees returning to employment following lockdowns now have higher disposable income (than received on PUP, EWSS, TWSS etc).\n- Increased consumer and business confidence: may encourage consumers to spend on deferred items like holidays.\n- Expectations of future price increases: with increasing demand, consumers may fear prices will rise and so buy now."},

    {num:3, label:"Q3: Minimum Unit Pricing & Market Failure",
     q:"Minimum Unit Pricing (MUP) for alcohol was introduced in Ireland in early 2022. A standard bottle of wine (750ml) cannot be sold for less than \u20ac7.40 and a can of beer (500ml) for less than \u20ac1.70.\n\n(a) Do you agree with this new MUP for alcohol? Justify your answer.\n\n(b) The purchase of alcohol in the free market may generate a market failure. Explain this statement using an example.",
     a:"(a) Arguments FOR MUP:\n- May combat alcohol abuse: the higher price may reduce consumption/binge drinking.\n- Less personal/social problems: reduced consumption leads to fewer social issues.\n- Reduced admissions to EDs: reduced consumption should lower hospital admissions, helping reduce health costs.\n- A healthier population: decreased per capita consumption may reduce absenteeism and increase productivity.\n\nArguments AGAINST MUP:\n- It is inequitable: as it is regressive, it will impact those on lowest incomes the most.\n- Cross border shopping: may lead to increased cross-border shopping, losing economic activity and tax revenue for the Republic.\n- Unnecessary state interference in personal decision making.\n- Effect on hidden economy: some may resort to alternative sources of alcohol.\n- Switch to alternative drugs: if other drugs are cheaper, demand for these may increase.\n\n(b) Market failure occurs when the price mechanism in the free market leads to an inefficient or inequitable allocation of resources. The production/consumption of alcohol may lead to consumers consuming harmful goods, being exploited, or generating negative externalities for third parties. For example, individual taxpayers who aren't involved in the consumption of alcohol end up paying for the healthcare of individuals who overconsume alcohol."},

    {num:4, label:"Q4: Circular Flow of Income & FDI",
     q:"(a) Categorise each of the following as either an injection or a leakage from the circular flow of income:\n1. The Irish government increases public sector salaries by 1% in 2023.\n2. Irish exports increase to record \u20ac160bn despite Covid-19.\n3. Irish consumers saved more than \u20ac10bn in the first quarter of 2021.\n\nAnswer either (b) or (c):\n(b) Justify each of your choices in part (a).\nOR\n(c) Outline two reasons why inflows of FDI into Ireland are important for the Irish economy.",
     a:"(a)\n1. Government increases public sector salaries = INJECTION\n2. Irish exports increase = INJECTION\n3. Irish consumers saved \u20ac10bn = LEAKAGE\n\n(b) Justifications:\n- Public sector salaries are part of government spending, so government spending is an injection into the circular flow of income.\n- Exports are money that originates outside the circular flow of income and thus is an injection.\n- By not spending their income, consumers are reducing the size of the circular flow, thus saving is a withdrawal/leakage.\n\n(c) Importance of FDI:\n1. Increased employment opportunities: with increased investment there will be increased demand for labour in new and expanding firms.\n2. Increased tax revenue: from corporation, capital gains, income and VAT taxation. With increased investment, employment, expenditure and profit, the government earns more tax revenue.\n3. Increased economic growth/exports: investment is an injection into the circular flow and will have a multiplier effect (C+I+G+X-M)."},

    {num:5, label:"Q5: Ageing Population",
     q:"It is predicted that the number of people in Ireland aged over 65 will have increased to 1 million by 2031.\n\n(a) Explain two factors which are likely to have influenced this trend in the Irish population.\n\nAnswer (b) or (c):\n(b) Outline two economic advantages of an ageing Irish population.\nOR\n(c) Outline two impacts Ireland's ageing population will have on future government policy.",
     a:"(a) Factors influencing the trend:\n1. Improvement in healthcare in Ireland: resulting in improved treatment of illness and reducing death rates.\n2. Improved standard of living / increased income / increased employment: allows people to buy better quality food, access healthcare and improved infrastructure.\n3. Increased focus on a healthy lifestyle in modern society: people are more conscious of maintaining a better lifestyle as they age.\n4. Improved planning by government and state agencies recognising the need for improved policies.\n\n(b) Economic advantages of ageing population:\n1. Increased numbers may participate in the labour force due to people living longer.\n2. More experienced workforce as these workers bring many years of experience.\n3. Skill shortages may be filled by retired workers returning to the workforce.\n4. Tax revenues: if older workers remain, it allows for increased tax revenue and less need for pensions.\n5. Opportunities for businesses: change in demand patterns may present opportunities e.g. over-55 holidays.\n\n(c) Impacts on government policy:\n1. Increased spending on healthcare or change in budget priorities for health care.\n2. Increased pressure on pensions / may need to means-test the contributory pension / increase pension age.\n3. More demands on government services e.g. health and long-term care.\n4. Possible increased tax burden for those remaining in the workforce.\n5. Labour market: may cause dependency ratio problems / reduced labour market participation rates."},

    {num:6, label:"Q6: Perfect Competition",
     q:"Firms in Perfect Competition are said to be Price-Takers.\n\n(a) On diagrams label and illustrate:\n(i) What happens to the market equilibrium as more firms enter the market?\n(ii) What happens to the individual firm's price as more firms enter the market?\nExplain each diagram.\n\nAnswer either (b) or (c):\n(b) Firms can survive in the short run even if they are making a loss. Explain.\nOR\n(c) In the long run only the most efficient firms will survive. Explain.",
     a:"(a) Explanation for the market:\nAs firms outside the industry become aware of the supernormal profits (SNPs) earned, they will enter the industry (no barriers to entry). As these firms enter, market supply shifts right from S1 to S2. Quantity supplied increases from Q1 to Q2 and the price decreases from P1 to P2.\n\nExplanation for the firm:\nAs the individual firm is a price-taker, it must accept the price established by the industry, thus its price also decreases from P1 to P2. The firm's demand curve (D=AR=MR) shifts down.\n\n(b) Short-run losses:\nIn the short run, if AR (Average Revenue) is greater than AVC (Average Variable Cost), the firm is making a loss but once it covers its average variable costs, it contributes towards its fixed costs. The loss from shutting down would be greater than the loss from continuing to operate.\n\n(c) Long-run efficiency:\nA firm is most efficient when producing at the minimum point of AC. If it is not producing at the minimum point of the average total cost curve in the long run, it is not being efficient. It will not be earning normal profit and will be forced due to inefficiency to leave the industry."},

    {num:7, label:"Q7: ECB Interest Rates",
     q:"Only one of the charts below accurately displays the trend in the ECB interest rate from 2000 to 2020.\n\n(a)(i) Identify which chart accurately displays the correct trend.\n(ii) Justify your choice.\n\n(b) Other than setting the base % interest rate, outline two other roles of the ECB.",
     a:"(a)(i) Figure A displays the correct trend.\n\n(ii) In the wake of the global financial crisis in 2007/2008, the ECB gradually dropped its base interest rate to zero percent in order to discourage saving and encourage borrowing, hoping to stimulate investment and economic growth in the European economy.\n\n(b) Other roles of the ECB:\n1. Ensure price stability: the ECB aims for an inflation rate of 2% during the medium term.\n2. Manages the eurozone's foreign currency reserves and the buying or selling of currencies to influence the price of the euro.\n3. Ensures that financial markets and institutions are well supervised by national authorities and that payment systems work well.\n4. Ensures the stability, safety and soundness of the financial system across the eurozone.\n5. Authorises production of euro banknotes by eurozone countries."},

    {num:8, label:"Q8: Hidden Economy & Supply Chains",
     q:"Brexit and possible supply chain issues have led to fewer illegal fireworks in Ireland during Halloween 2021.\n\n(a) Explain what is meant by the economic term hidden economy.\n\n(b) Outline two reasons for the supply chain issues which many companies experienced in Ireland during 2021-2022.",
     a:"(a) The hidden economy refers to economic activity that is not recorded or declared to the authorities. It includes illegal activities (e.g. drug dealing, smuggling) and legal activities where income is not declared for tax purposes (e.g. cash-in-hand work). This results in a loss of tax revenue for the government and inaccurate national income statistics.\n\n(b) Reasons for supply chain issues:\n1. COVID-19 pandemic: lockdowns and restrictions globally led to factory closures, reduced production, and shipping delays, creating bottlenecks in global supply chains.\n2. Brexit: new customs checks, tariffs, and regulatory barriers between the UK and EU created delays and increased costs for goods moving through or from the UK to Ireland."},

    {num:9, label:"Q9: Social Costs & Benefits (Solar Panels)",
     q:"(a) Identify one private cost and one private benefit for the consumer of installing solar panels.\n\n(b) Installing solar panels also creates social benefits. Discuss this statement.",
     a:"(a)\nPrivate cost: The initial financial outlay/expense of purchasing and installing the solar panels (can be several thousand euro).\nPrivate benefit: Reduced electricity bills over time / the consumer generates their own electricity and may even sell surplus back to the grid.\n\n(b) Social benefits of solar panels:\n- Reduced carbon emissions: solar energy is a renewable, clean energy source that reduces reliance on fossil fuels, helping to combat climate change.\n- Reduced air pollution: fewer harmful emissions lead to improved public health.\n- Reduced strain on the national grid: if many households generate their own electricity, it reduces demand on the grid.\n- Energy security: reduces Ireland's dependence on imported fossil fuels.\n- Job creation in the renewable energy sector."},

    {num:10, label:"Q10: Production Possibility Frontier (PPF)",
     q:"PepsiCo has 23 brands. Doritos and Tropicana are two of their most popular products.\n\n(a) Calculate the opportunity cost of PepsiCo moving production from point D to point H on the PPF curve. (D = 50 Doritos, 62 Tropicana; H = 90 Doritos, 0 Tropicana). Explain your answer.\n\n(b) The point X (20,20) is another production possibility for PepsiCo. Would you recommend them to produce at this point? Explain.",
     a:"(a) Moving from D to H:\n- Doritos increase from 50m kg to 90m kg (gain of 40m kg)\n- Tropicana decreases from 62m litres to 0 litres (loss of 62m litres)\nOpportunity cost = 62 million litres of Tropicana given up to gain 40 million kg of Doritos.\nFor every extra 1m kg of Doritos, PepsiCo gives up 1.55m litres of Tropicana.\n\n(b) No, producing at point X (20,20) would not be recommended. This point lies inside the PPF curve, which means PepsiCo would be producing inefficiently - they would not be making full use of their available resources. They could produce more of both products with their current resources. An efficient firm should produce on the PPF boundary."},

    // ===== SECTION B: Extended Response Questions (225 marks) =====
    {num:11, label:"Q11: Rental Market, Land & Regional Development",
     q:"(a)(i) Outline two possible reasons for the disparity in average rents between Dublin City and Waterford City in Q2, 2021.\n(ii) Outline two possible interventions the Irish government could pursue to support balanced regional development.\n\n(b)(i) Explain, with a fully labelled diagram, how the equilibrium price of land is determined.\n(ii) Other than land being fixed in supply, outline two characteristics of land.\n(iii) Explain how derived demand relates to the factor of production land.\n\n(c)(i) Explain the term opportunity cost.\n(ii) Outline one opportunity cost of government expenditure on the North Runway Project at Dublin Airport.\n(iii) Discuss the arguments for and against the Irish government providing more financial support to regional airports.",
     a:"(a)(i) Reasons for rent disparity:\n1. Higher demand for rental properties in Dublin due to greater employment opportunities, multinational firms, and universities.\n2. Limited supply of rental properties in Dublin relative to demand, driving up prices. Waterford has lower demand and more affordable supply.\n\n(ii) Government interventions for balanced regional development:\n1. Decentralisation of government departments and agencies to regional cities to create employment outside Dublin.\n2. Investment in infrastructure (roads, broadband, public transport) in regional areas to attract businesses.\n\n(b)(i) The equilibrium price of land (economic rent) is determined by demand alone, since the supply of land is perfectly inelastic (fixed/vertical supply curve). The demand curve for land is downward sloping. Where demand intersects the fixed supply curve determines the equilibrium rent/price.\n\n(ii) Characteristics of land:\n1. Land is a gift of nature - it is not man-made and exists naturally.\n2. Land has no cost of production - since it is a natural resource, there is no cost involved in creating it.\n3. Land is geographically immobile - it cannot be moved from one location to another.\n4. Land varies in quality/fertility.\n\n(iii) Derived demand: Land is not demanded for its own sake but because of what can be produced on it. The demand for land is derived from the demand for the goods and services produced using land. For example, if demand for housing increases, demand for building land increases.\n\n(c)(i) Opportunity cost is the cost of the next best alternative forgone when a choice is made. When resources are used for one purpose, the benefit that could have been gained from the next best use is lost.\n\n(ii) The opportunity cost of spending \u20ac250m-\u20ac500m on the North Runway could be investment in healthcare, social housing, or education. For example, these funds could have been used to build thousands of social housing units.\n\n(iii) Arguments FOR supporting regional airports:\n- Balanced regional development: keeps economic activity outside Dublin.\n- Tourism: regional airports attract tourists to areas like Kerry, benefiting the local economy.\n- Business connectivity: important for business investment in regional areas.\n\nArguments AGAINST:\n- Opportunity cost: funds could be better spent on other infrastructure like roads or broadband.\n- Low passenger numbers may not justify the investment.\n- Environmental concerns: subsidising air travel conflicts with climate targets."},

    {num:12, label:"Q12: Market Structures & Electricity Market",
     q:"(a)(i) Comment on what the HHI results indicate about market concentration in the electricity industry (2005 to 2019). HHI was 10,000 in 2005 and 3,328 in 2019.\n(ii) Explain two reasons why a government would decide to deregulate its electricity supply.\n(iii) Explain the term privatisation.\n(iv) Outline one reason why a government may choose privatisation over deregulation.\n\n(b)(i) Outline one advantage of both a State Monopoly and an Oligopoly.\n(ii) Explain, with a diagram, the long-run equilibrium position of a monopoly firm.\n(iii) Explain two changes in market conditions which allow a market to move from a Monopoly to an Oligopoly.\n\n(c)(i) Outline two challenges the Irish economy faces in transforming the motor industry into a carbon neutral industry.\n(ii) Discuss one reason for and one reason against granting planning permission for additional data centres in Ireland.",
     a:"(a)(i) HHI Commentary:\nIn 2005, the HHI was 10,000 indicating a pure monopoly (ESB was the sole supplier). By 2019, the HHI dropped to 3,328, indicating the market has become much more competitive though still highly concentrated (HHI above 2,500 = highly concentrated). The market moved from monopoly to oligopoly through deregulation.\n\n(ii) Reasons for deregulation:\n1. Increased competition: more firms entering the market leads to lower prices for consumers, greater choice, and improved quality of service.\n2. Increased efficiency: competition forces firms to become more efficient to survive, reducing waste and improving service.\n\n(iii) Privatisation is the transfer of ownership of a state-owned/semi-state enterprise to private ownership, usually through the sale of shares to the public.\n\n(iv) A government may choose privatisation because it generates immediate revenue from the sale of the semi-state body, whereas deregulation does not directly raise revenue. The sale proceeds can be used for other government spending priorities.\n\n(b)(i) Advantage of Monopoly: Economies of scale - a monopoly can produce at lower average costs due to large-scale production, and these savings can be passed on to consumers.\nAdvantage of Oligopoly: Product differentiation and innovation - oligopolistic firms compete through non-price competition, leading to greater innovation and product variety for consumers.\n\n(ii) Monopoly long-run equilibrium:\nThe monopolist produces where MC = MR (profit-maximising output). Price is read off the AR (demand) curve above this point. The monopolist earns supernormal profit because AR > AC at the profit-maximising output. There is no entry of new firms due to barriers to entry, so supernormal profits persist in the long run.\n\n(iii) Changes allowing move from Monopoly to Oligopoly:\n1. Removal of barriers to entry: deregulation/legislation changes allow new firms to enter the market and compete.\n2. End of exclusive government licenses/franchises: removing the legal protection that gave the monopolist exclusive rights to supply.\n\n(c)(i) Challenges for carbon neutral motor industry:\n1. Insufficient charging infrastructure: Ireland needs a massive investment in electric vehicle charging points across the country.\n2. High cost of electric vehicles: EVs are currently more expensive than traditional cars, making them unaffordable for many consumers.\n\n(ii) Data centres:\nReason FOR: Job creation and economic growth - data centres create high-skilled employment and attract further FDI into Ireland, increasing tax revenue.\nReason AGAINST: Energy consumption - data centres could account for 29% of all electricity demand by 2028, putting strain on the national grid and conflicting with Ireland's climate targets."},

    {num:13, label:"Q13: Government Revenue, Expenditure & Taxation",
     q:"The infographic shows sources of income and expenditure as a proportion of every euro the Irish government receives and spends in 2020.\n\n(a)(i) Explain why social benefits represent such a high proportion of government expenditure. Use an example.\n(ii) Distinguish between direct and indirect tax with examples.\n\n(b)(i) Outline one possible incentive the government uses to encourage certain behaviour and one tax measure to discourage certain behaviour.\n(ii) Outline two interventions, other than incentives/taxes, that a government could implement to influence consumer behaviour.\n\n(c) The Irish Government has signed up to the OECD agreement on a minimum global corporation tax rate of 15%. Discuss.",
     a:"(a)(i) Social benefits represent a high proportion because the government has a responsibility to provide a social safety net for citizens. During 2020, COVID-19 led to massive increases in social welfare payments (PUP, EWSS, TWSS) as unemployment surged due to lockdowns. Example: Pandemic Unemployment Payment (PUP) of \u20ac350 per week was paid to hundreds of thousands of workers who lost their jobs.\n\n(ii) Direct tax is levied directly on income or wealth and is paid directly to the Revenue Commissioners by the taxpayer. It cannot be passed on. Examples: PAYE (income tax), Capital Gains Tax, Corporation Tax.\nIndirect tax is levied on goods and services and is included in the price of the product. It can be passed on from the producer to the consumer. Examples: VAT, Excise Duty, Customs Duty.\n\n(b)(i) Incentive to encourage behaviour: The government offers tax relief on pension contributions to encourage people to save for retirement. This reduces taxable income, incentivising long-term saving.\nTax measure to discourage behaviour: High excise duty on cigarettes to discourage smoking. The higher price reduces demand and consumption of harmful tobacco products.\n\n(ii) Government interventions to influence behaviour:\n1. Legislation/regulation: e.g. banning smoking in workplaces or introducing a sugar tax to reduce consumption of unhealthy products.\n2. Information campaigns/education: e.g. public health campaigns warning about the dangers of alcohol or promoting healthy eating habits.\n\n(c) Arguments FOR the 15% minimum rate:\n- Levels the playing field: prevents a race to the bottom on corporation tax rates between countries.\n- Increases government revenue: Ireland will collect more tax from multinational profits.\n- International cooperation: shows Ireland is committed to fair international tax practices.\n\nArguments AGAINST:\n- Loss of competitive advantage: Ireland's low 12.5% rate was a key attraction for FDI. Moving to 15% may make Ireland less attractive.\n- Impact on FDI: some multinationals may relocate to countries that offer other advantages.\n- May reduce employment as some MNCs reconsider their Irish operations."},

    {num:14, label:"Q14: Demand & Supply, Consumer Behaviour",
     q:"Section B question covering demand and supply analysis, consumer behaviour, and market equilibrium.",
     a:"Key economic concepts covered:\n\n- Demand curves slope downward due to the law of demand (inverse relationship between price and quantity demanded).\n- Supply curves slope upward as higher prices incentivise producers to supply more.\n- Market equilibrium occurs where demand equals supply.\n- Consumer surplus is the difference between what consumers are willing to pay and what they actually pay.\n- Changes in conditions of demand (income, tastes, price of substitutes/complements) shift the demand curve.\n- Changes in conditions of supply (costs, technology, government policy) shift the supply curve."},

    {num:15, label:"Q15: International Trade & Economic Development",
     q:"Section B question on international trade, comparative advantage, and economic development.",
     a:"Key concepts:\n\n- Free trade allows countries to specialise in goods where they have a comparative advantage, increasing overall output and efficiency.\n- Arguments for protectionism: protecting infant industries, safeguarding employment, national security, preventing dumping.\n- Arguments for free trade: lower prices, greater choice, increased competition, access to larger markets.\n- The EU Single Market provides Ireland with access to a market of over 440 million consumers.\n- Exchange rates affect competitiveness of exports and cost of imports."},

    {num:16, label:"Q16: Economic Growth & Development",
     q:"Section B question covering economic growth, sustainability, and government policy.",
     a:"Key concepts:\n\n- Economic growth is measured by increases in real GDP/GNP.\n- Sustainable development meets the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs.\n- Government uses fiscal policy (taxation and spending) and supply-side policies to promote growth.\n- The multiplier effect means an initial injection of spending leads to a larger overall increase in national income.\n- Infrastructure investment, education, and innovation are key drivers of long-term economic growth."}
  ],

  "2023": [
    // ===== SECTION A: Short Response Questions (100 marks) =====
    {num:1, label:"Q1: Supply Curve & Price Discrimination",
     q:"France will host the Rugby World Cup in 2023.\n\n(a) Explain, with the aid of a fully labelled diagram (including the axes), the supply curve for tickets for this event.\n\n(b) Explain two conditions necessary for price discrimination to occur in the selling of tickets for the Rugby World Cup 2023.",
     a:"(a) The supply curve for tickets is perfectly inelastic (vertical line). Regardless of price, the quantity of seats supplied will be fixed for the stadiums used for the event. Even if price changes, the venues can only accommodate a certain number of attendees. The supply curve is vertical, reflecting the fact that venues have a fixed capacity.\nDiagram: Price on Y-axis, Quantity on X-axis, vertical line at the fixed capacity.\n\n(b) Conditions for price discrimination:\n1. Consumer ignorance: The consumer is unaware that price discrimination is taking place.\n2. Consumer indifference: Consumers are aware of the price discrimination but don't care about it.\n3. Consumer attitudes: Consumers feel it is worth paying more rather than go without.\n4. Monopoly power: The firm must have some degree of monopoly power, otherwise rival firms would undercut prices.\n5. Different price elasticities of demand: The firm must recognise that different customers are more or less responsive to price changes (e.g. pensioners and students are more price elastic).\n6. Market separation: It must be impossible for customers to buy in the cheaper market and resell in the more expensive market."},

    {num:2, label:"Q2: Price Elasticity of Demand (Petrol)",
     q:"On the 3rd of March, 2022 the price of petrol in Ireland broke the \u20ac2 barrier for the first time.\n\n(a) Select if petrol has price elastic or price inelastic demand. Explain your answer.\n\nAnswer (b) or (c):\n(b) Outline two reasons why it is important for retailers to understand the concept of price elasticity of demand.\nOR\n(c) Outline one advantage and one disadvantage for the Irish economy of the Minister for Finance's decision not to increase excise duties on petrol in Budget 2023.",
     a:"(a) Petrol has PRICE INELASTIC demand. If price increases, the percentage increase in price will be greater than the percentage decrease in quantity demanded. Petrol is a necessity for many motorists - if price rises, consumers still need petrol and demand will fall by a lower proportion.\n\n(b) Importance for retailers:\n1. They will know by how much quantity demanded will change if the price of the product is changed.\n2. They will know how to maximise revenue: for goods with inelastic PED, firms should increase price; for goods with elastic PED, firms should decrease price.\n3. Price discrimination: before a firm considers charging multiple prices, it needs to identify consumers with different PEDs.\n4. Impact and incidence of taxation: the firm will decide how much of an indirect tax to pass on to the consumer based upon their PED.\n\n(c) Advantage of NOT increasing excise duties:\n- Cost of Living Crisis: Irish citizens are already struggling to maintain their standard of living due to constant inflationary pressures throughout 2022. An increase in excise duties would have further exacerbated this problem.\n- Doesn't penalise businesses: any increase would have created further increases in costs of production for firms already struggling to survive.\n\nDisadvantage of NOT increasing excise duties:\n- Government revenue: petrol has price inelastic demand, so increases in excise duties generate large increases in revenue for the government.\n- Environmental damage: tax increases are a disincentive to consume. Without increasing this disincentive, consumers will continue to purchase this environmentally harmful product."},

    {num:3, label:"Q3: Utility & Consumer Behaviour",
     q:"(a) Complete the missing total utility and marginal utility figures in the table below. Show your workings.\nUnits consumed: 1, 2, 3, 4\nTotal Utility: 40, 80, ?, 137\nMarginal Utility: 40, ?, 35, ?\n\nAnswer (b) or (c):\n(b) At what point does the law of diminishing marginal utility set in? Explain.\nOR\n(c) Does the formula MUx/Px = 1800/10 and MUy/Py = 3600/10 obey the Equi-Marginal Principle? Explain.",
     a:"(a) Workings:\n- MU of 2nd unit: 80 - 40 = 40\n- TU of 3rd unit: 80 + 35 = 115\n- MU of 4th unit: 137 - 115 = 22\n\nCompleted table:\nUnits: 1, 2, 3, 4\nTotal Utility: 40, 80, 115, 137\nMarginal Utility: 40, 40, 35, 22\n\n(b) The law of diminishing marginal utility sets in on the consumption of the third unit (after the consumption of the second unit). Marginal utility declines from 40 to 35 utils. The law states that as a consumer consumes additional units of a good, the extra satisfaction (marginal utility) gained from each successive unit will eventually begin to decrease.\n\n(c) No, the formula does NOT obey the Equi-Marginal Principle.\n1800 / 10 = 180\n3600 / 10 = 360\nThe ratio is not the same (180 does not equal 360). For the Equi-Marginal Principle to hold, MUx/Px must equal MUy/Py. The consumer should reallocate spending from good X to good Y until the ratios are equal."},

    {num:4, label:"Q4: Costs of Production",
     q:"The table below shows the output and total costs in a firm.\nOutput: 1, 2, 3, 4\nTotal Cost: \u20ac55, \u20ac82, \u20ac108, \u20ac152\nAverage Cost: 55, ?, 36, ?\nMarginal Cost: N/A, 27, ?, ?\n\n(a) Complete the missing average cost and marginal cost figures.\n\nAnswer (b) or (c):\n(b) To remain in production, in the short run a firm must cover its average total costs. Agree or disagree? Explain.\nOR\n(c) Explain the relationship between the Marginal Cost Curve and the Average Cost Curve.",
     a:"(a) Workings:\n- AC at 2 units: 82 / 2 = \u20ac41\n- MC at 3 units: 108 - 82 = \u20ac26\n- AC at 4 units: 152 / 4 = \u20ac38\n- MC at 4 units: 152 - 108 = \u20ac44\n\nCompleted table:\nOutput: 1, 2, 3, 4\nTotal Cost: \u20ac55, \u20ac82, \u20ac108, \u20ac152\nAverage Cost: \u20ac55, \u20ac41, \u20ac36, \u20ac38\nMarginal Cost: N/A, \u20ac27, \u20ac26, \u20ac44\n\n(b) DISAGREE. In the short run a firm must cover its average variable costs (not average total costs) while waiting for an increase in price of output or a reduction in total costs. Even if the firm is making a loss, as long as AR > AVC, it is making a contribution to its fixed costs and should continue to produce.\n\n(c) Relationship between MC and AC curves:\n- When Marginal Cost is greater than Average Cost: Average Cost is rising.\n- When Marginal Cost is less than Average Cost: Average Cost is falling.\n- When Marginal Cost is equal to Average Cost: Average Cost is at its minimum. The MC curve intersects the AC curve at its lowest point."},

    {num:5, label:"Q5: Production Possibility Frontier",
     q:"The diagram shows the Production Possibilities Frontier for a digital manufacturing company that produces both laptops and tablet devices.\n\n(a) Identify from the diagram which option (A, B or C) represents an efficient, an inefficient, and an impossible production point.\n\n(b) Justify each of your choices.",
     a:"(a)\nEfficient Production Point: C (on the PPF boundary)\nInefficient Production Point: A (inside the PPF boundary)\nImpossible Production Point: B (outside the PPF boundary)\n\n(b) Justifications:\n- Efficient (C): An efficient production point is where the firm is making the best possible use of scarce resources. It is producing as much as it can given current resources. This can be seen anywhere on the PPF boundary.\n- Inefficient (A): An inefficient production point is where the firm is wasteful of scarce resources. It is possible to produce more tablets and laptops given current resources. This is any point inside the PPF boundary.\n- Impossible (B): An impossible production point is one which the firm cannot currently produce given their current scarce resources. To produce at this level, they would need to increase their factors of production. This is any point outside the PPF boundary."},

    {num:6, label:"Q6: Direct & Indirect Taxation",
     q:"(a) In each case, indicate whether the tax is direct or indirect:\n- VAT\n- PAYE\n- Customs and Excise Duty\n\n(b) Outline three canons/principles of taxation which are achieved through the use of direct taxes.",
     a:"(a)\n- VAT: Indirect Tax\n- PAYE: Direct Tax\n- Customs and Excise Duty: Indirect Tax\n\n(b) Canons/principles of taxation:\n1. Certainty: It should be clear and unambiguous to the taxpayer the amount they are required to pay and the reason for doing so.\n2. Convenience: The tax should be levied at a time and in a manner which is most convenient for the taxpayer to pay (e.g. PAYE is deducted at source).\n3. Equity: The tax system should operate fairly. An equitable tax system should take a larger amount from those who are more able to pay than others (progressive taxation).\n4. Economy: The cost of tax collection should be far exceeded by the amount of tax which is collected.\n5. Should not act as a disincentive to save/work/invest: No tax should negatively affect those willing to supply their labour or discourage entrepreneurs from investing.\n6. Evasion should be impossible: Otherwise the tax is not effective in raising revenue."},

    {num:7, label:"Q7: Housing Market & Vacant Property Tax",
     q:"Landlords are leaving the Irish housing market in their thousands, blaming excessive taxation, rent control and constantly changing laws.\n\n(a) Show on the diagram how this development will alter the rental market equilibrium position. Explain your answer.\n\n(b) Outline two reasons why the Irish government introduced the vacant property tax.",
     a:"(a) As landlords leave the market, the supply of rental properties decreases. The supply curve shifts to the left from S to S1. The equilibrium price increases from Pe to Pe1, and the equilibrium quantity decreases from Qe to Qe1. This means rents will rise and fewer properties are available.\n\n(b) Reasons for vacant property tax:\n1. Increased government revenue to help with the homelessness/housing crisis.\n2. Vacant properties represent a market failure: in a market where some consumers are unable to find a home, vacant properties represent a waste of scarce resources. The tax incentivises owners to bring properties into use.\n3. More equitable: some vacant properties are holiday homes (second households). A progressive tax system should take a higher proportion from owners of greater wealth.\n4. Increased pressure on the Irish housing market year on year, exacerbated further by the war in Ukraine."},

    {num:8, label:"Q8: ECB & Monetary Policy",
     q:"Eurozone interest rates increased four times in the last six months of 2022.\n\n(a) Justify why the European Central Bank (ECB) made this decision.\n\n(b) Does being a member of the Eurozone affect Ireland's ability to implement monetary policy in Ireland? Explain.",
     a:"(a) The ECB increased interest rates to combat rising inflation in the eurozone. Following the COVID-19 pandemic and the war in Ukraine, inflation surged due to supply chain disruptions and rising energy prices. Higher interest rates discourage borrowing and encourage saving, which reduces aggregate demand in the economy, helping to bring inflation back down towards the ECB's 2% target.\n\n(b) Yes, being a member of the Eurozone significantly affects Ireland's ability to implement monetary policy. Ireland has given up control of its own monetary policy to the ECB. Ireland cannot independently set interest rates, control money supply, or adjust exchange rates. The ECB sets a single monetary policy for all 20 eurozone members, which may not always suit Ireland's specific economic conditions. For example, interest rates set to cool inflation in Germany may be inappropriate for Ireland's economy."},

    {num:9, label:"Q9: Diminishing Marginal Returns & Specialisation",
     q:"China is the world's powerhouse in manufacturing goods e.g. clothing. Its share of world exports dwarfs every other nation.\n\n(a) Explain the economic concept of the law of diminishing marginal returns.\n\n(b) Outline two cost advantages China's firms experience through specialisation.",
     a:"(a) The Law of Diminishing Marginal Returns states that as more and more units of a variable factor of production (e.g. labour) are added to a fixed factor (e.g. capital/land), there comes a point where the extra output (marginal product) produced by each additional unit of the variable factor will begin to decrease. This assumes at least one factor is fixed (short run) and technology remains constant.\n\n(b) Cost advantages of specialisation for China:\n1. Lower average costs through economies of scale: by specialising in manufacturing, China's firms produce huge volumes, spreading fixed costs over millions of units and achieving very low average costs per unit.\n2. Increased productivity/expertise: workers who specialise in specific tasks become highly skilled and efficient at those tasks, increasing output per worker and reducing labour costs per unit.\n3. Reduced training costs: when workers focus on specific tasks, less time and money is spent on training.\n4. Bulk buying of raw materials: large-scale specialised production allows firms to negotiate lower prices for inputs."},

    {num:10, label:"Q10: National Income Accounts (GNP, GNI, Modified GNI)",
     q:"Given that GDP at Current Market Prices was \u20ac426bn, use the information to calculate B (Gross National Income at CMP) and C (Modified Gross National Income at CMP).\n\nData: Net Factor Income from Abroad: -\u20ac103bn; EU Subsidies: \u20ac1.7bn; EU Taxes: \u20ac0.5bn; Adjustments (redomiciled companies, depreciation on R&D/IP, aircraft leasing): \u20ac89bn.\n\nA = GNP at CMP = \u20ac323bn (given).",
     a:"A = GNP at CMP:\nGDP at CMP + Net Factor Income from Abroad\n= \u20ac426bn + (-\u20ac103bn) = \u20ac323bn (given)\n\nB = Gross National Income at CMP:\nGNP at CMP + EU Subsidies - EU Taxes\n= \u20ac323bn + \u20ac1.7bn - \u20ac0.5bn\n= \u20ac324.2bn\n\nC = Modified Gross National Income (GNI*) at CMP:\nGNI at CMP - Adjustments\n= \u20ac324.2bn - \u20ac89bn\n= \u20ac235.2bn\n\nWhy this matters: Modified GNI (GNI*) was developed by the CSO to provide a more accurate measure of the size of the Irish economy. Standard GDP and GNP figures are distorted by the activities of large multinationals (profit repatriation, intellectual property, aircraft leasing). GNI* strips out these distortions to give a truer picture of the domestic economy."},

    // ===== SECTION B: Extended Response Questions (300 marks) =====
    {num:11, label:"Q11: Population, Labour & Human Development",
     q:"(a)(i) Calculate the percentage change in the Irish population from 2016 to 2022. (Population 2016: 4,761,865; Population 2022: 5,123,536; Change: 361,671)\n(ii) Explain two factors which influenced this trend.\n(iii) Discuss one negative and one positive effect of population increase on government finances.\n\n(b)(i) Explain the factor of production labour.\n(ii) Explain two factors that influence geographical mobility of labour.\n(iii) Explain two ways the government can increase geographical mobility of labour.\n\n(c)(i) If average life expectancy in Ireland decreased, would it positively or negatively affect Ireland's HDI score? Explain.\n(ii) Despite Ireland's high HDI ranking, inequalities still exist. Outline two economic policies to address inequality.\n(iii) Outline two possible economic disadvantages of implementing these policies.",
     a:"(a)(i) Percentage change = (361,671 / 4,761,865) x 100 = 7.6% increase\n\n(ii) Factors influencing population growth:\n1. Immigration: Ireland's strong economy attracted significant numbers of immigrants, particularly from EU countries and further afield, for employment opportunities.\n2. Natural increase: birth rates exceeded death rates, contributing to population growth. Improved healthcare and living standards contributed to lower death rates.\n\n(iii) Positive effect: Increased tax revenue - more people working means more income tax, VAT, and other tax revenues for the government.\nNegative effect: Increased government expenditure - more people require public services such as healthcare, education, housing, and infrastructure, putting pressure on government spending.\n\n(b)(i) Labour refers to all human effort, both mental and physical, used in the production of goods and services. It includes all workers from manual labourers to highly skilled professionals.\n\n(ii) Factors affecting geographical mobility:\n1. Housing availability and affordability: Workers may be unable to move to areas where jobs are available if housing is too expensive or unavailable (e.g. Dublin's housing crisis).\n2. Family/social ties: Workers may be reluctant to move away from family, friends, and community connections.\n\n(iii) Government measures to increase geographical mobility:\n1. Investment in housing: building more affordable housing in areas of economic growth to allow workers to relocate.\n2. Investment in transport infrastructure: improving roads, rail, and public transport to allow workers to commute rather than relocate, or to make relocation easier.\n\n(c)(i) It would NEGATIVELY affect Ireland's HDI score. Life expectancy at birth is one of the three components of the HDI (along with education and GNI per capita). A decrease in life expectancy would lower the health component, thus reducing Ireland's overall HDI score.\n\n(ii) Policies to address inequality:\n1. Progressive taxation: increasing the tax rate for higher earners so they contribute proportionally more, with revenue redistributed through social welfare and public services.\n2. Investment in education: providing equal access to quality education for all, including grants and subsidies for disadvantaged students.\n\n(iii) Disadvantages of these policies:\n1. Brain drain/emigration: higher taxes on high earners may cause skilled workers to emigrate to countries with lower tax rates.\n2. Increased government debt: funding these policies may require increased government borrowing if tax revenue is insufficient."},

    {num:12, label:"Q12: Market Structures (Perfect Competition, Oligopoly, Windfall Tax)",
     q:"(a)(i) Identify three characteristics of a perfectly competitive market.\n(ii) Identify one reason why the market for Irish milk can no longer be considered perfectly competitive.\n(iii) Explain, with a diagram, the long-run equilibrium of a firm in perfect competition.\n\n(b)(i) Based on the market share figures (Kerry Group 48%, Glanbia 27%, Dairygold 8%, Lakeland 7%, Dale Farm 3%, Aurivo 3%, Arrabawn 2%, Tipperary Co-op 2%), calculate the HHI for Irish Dairy Producers.\n(ii) Is this market competitive, moderately concentrated, or highly concentrated? Explain.\n(iii) Outline one advantage and one disadvantage of a perfectly competitive market.\n\n(c) Budget 2023 proposed a temporary 33% windfall tax on energy companies' profits. Discuss arguments for and against.",
     a:"(a)(i) Characteristics of perfect competition:\n1. Large number of buyers and sellers - no single buyer or seller can influence the market price.\n2. Homogeneous (identical) products - all firms sell the same product.\n3. Perfect knowledge - all buyers and sellers have full information about prices and products.\n4. Free entry and exit - no barriers to entering or leaving the industry.\n5. Price-takers - individual firms must accept the market price.\n\n(ii) The market for Irish milk is no longer perfectly competitive because firms now differentiate their products (low-fat milk, super milk, lactose-free milk, organic milk). Product differentiation means products are no longer homogeneous.\n\n(iii) Long-run equilibrium in perfect competition:\nIn the long run, firms in perfect competition earn only normal profit. The firm produces where MC = MR = AR = AC at the minimum point of the AC curve.\nDiagram: U-shaped AC curve with MC cutting through its minimum point. Price line (D=AR=MR) is horizontal and tangent to the minimum point of AC. Output is at Q where MC = MR.\nExplanation: If supernormal profits existed, new firms would enter (no barriers), increasing supply, pushing down price until only normal profit remains. If losses existed, firms would exit, reducing supply, pushing up price until normal profit is restored.\n\n(b)(i) HHI Calculation:\nHHI = 48\u00b2 + 27\u00b2 + 8\u00b2 + 7\u00b2 + 3\u00b2 + 3\u00b2 + 2\u00b2 + 2\u00b2\n= 2,304 + 729 + 64 + 49 + 9 + 9 + 4 + 4\n= 3,172\n\n(ii) The market is HIGHLY CONCENTRATED. An HHI above 2,500 indicates a highly concentrated market. Kerry Group alone holds 48% market share, and the top two firms (Kerry Group and Glanbia) control 75% of the market. This is an oligopoly.\n\n(iii) Advantage of perfectly competitive market: Allocative efficiency - resources are allocated efficiently as price equals marginal cost (P = MC), ensuring that the right amount of goods is produced.\nDisadvantage: No product variety - since products are homogeneous, consumers have no choice in terms of product differentiation or branding.\n\n(c) Arguments FOR the windfall tax:\n- Fairness/equity: energy companies earned excessive profits due to the energy crisis caused by the war in Ukraine, not through innovation or efficiency. It is fair to tax these windfall gains.\n- Revenue generation: the windfall tax would generate significant revenue that could fund energy credits and support vulnerable households during the cost of living crisis.\n- Consumer protection: excess profits suggest consumers are being overcharged, and the tax redistributes some of this back.\n\nArguments AGAINST:\n- Discourages investment: energy companies may reduce investment in new energy infrastructure and renewable energy if they fear future windfall taxes.\n- Uncertainty: creates uncertainty for businesses and may deter FDI in the energy sector.\n- Difficult to implement: defining what constitutes 'excess' or 'windfall' profit is subjective and could lead to legal challenges."},

    {num:13, label:"Q13: Circular Flow of Income, Multiplier & Fiscal Policy",
     q:"(a)(i) Draw a fully labelled diagram showing the Circular Flow of Income for an open economy.\n(ii) Explain the terms injections and leakages with two examples of each.\n\n(b)(i) Using the multiplier formula, calculate the multiplier. State the relationship used.\n(ii) Explain the economic significance of the multiplier.\n(iii) Outline two limitations of the multiplier concept.\n\n(c)(i) Explain the term fiscal policy.\n(ii) Outline two fiscal policy measures the government could use to stimulate the economy.\n(iii) Discuss one advantage and one disadvantage of using fiscal policy.",
     a:"(a)(i) Circular Flow diagram should show:\n- Households and Firms as the two main sectors\n- Flow of factors of production from households to firms\n- Flow of income (wages, rent, interest, profit) from firms to households\n- Flow of expenditure from households to firms\n- Flow of goods and services from firms to households\n- Injections: Investment (I), Government Spending (G), Exports (X)\n- Leakages: Savings (S), Taxation (T), Imports (M)\n\n(ii) Injections are flows of money INTO the circular flow of income that increase its size.\nExample 1: Investment (I) - spending by firms on capital goods (machinery, equipment).\nExample 2: Government Spending (G) - government expenditure on public services, infrastructure.\n\nLeakages are flows of money OUT of the circular flow that reduce its size.\nExample 1: Savings (S) - income not spent by households that is saved in financial institutions.\nExample 2: Imports (M) - spending on goods and services produced in other countries.\n\n(b)(i) Multiplier = 1 / (1 - MPC) or 1 / (MPT + MPS + MPM)\nThe multiplier shows the number of times by which a change in investment/injection will be multiplied to give the final change in national income.\n\n(ii) Economic significance: The multiplier indicates that an initial injection of spending into the economy will have a larger overall effect on national income. For example, if the multiplier is 2, an initial injection of \u20ac1 billion will ultimately increase national income by \u20ac2 billion, as the injection circulates through the economy.\n\n(iii) Limitations of the multiplier:\n1. Time lag: the full multiplier effect takes time to work through the economy and may not materialise as quickly as expected.\n2. Leakages may be larger than estimated: if savings, taxation, or imports are higher than expected, the actual multiplier effect will be smaller.\n\n(c)(i) Fiscal policy refers to the government's use of taxation and public expenditure to influence the level of economic activity in the economy.\n\n(ii) Fiscal policy measures to stimulate the economy:\n1. Reduce income tax: gives consumers more disposable income, increasing consumer spending and aggregate demand.\n2. Increase government capital expenditure: investment in infrastructure (roads, hospitals, schools) directly creates employment and stimulates demand through the multiplier effect.\n\n(iii) Advantage: Direct impact - government can target specific sectors or groups in need of stimulus.\nDisadvantage: Time lags - it takes time to implement fiscal policy changes (budget process) and for the effects to be felt in the economy."},

    {num:14, label:"Q14: Inflation, Exchange Rates & Trade",
     q:"Section B question covering inflation, exchange rates, and international trade issues facing the Irish economy.",
     a:"Key concepts:\n\n- Inflation is a sustained increase in the general price level. Measured by the Consumer Price Index (CPI).\n- Causes: Demand-pull inflation (excess demand in the economy) and Cost-push inflation (rising costs of production).\n- Effects of inflation: Reduced purchasing power, redistribution of income (hurts fixed-income earners), uncertainty for businesses, loss of international competitiveness.\n- Exchange rates: The price of one currency in terms of another. Affects export competitiveness and import costs.\n- A strong euro makes Irish exports more expensive abroad but imports cheaper.\n- Ireland, as a small open economy, is particularly vulnerable to exchange rate fluctuations.\n- Balance of Payments: records all economic transactions between Ireland and the rest of the world."},

    {num:15, label:"Q15: Market Failure & Government Intervention",
     q:"Section B question covering market failure, externalities, public goods, and the role of government intervention.",
     a:"Key concepts:\n\n- Market failure occurs when the free market leads to an inefficient or inequitable allocation of resources.\n- Types: Externalities (positive and negative), public goods, merit goods, demerit goods, monopoly power, information asymmetry.\n- Negative externalities: Costs imposed on third parties not involved in the transaction (e.g. pollution).\n- Positive externalities: Benefits enjoyed by third parties (e.g. education benefits society).\n- Government interventions: Taxation, subsidies, regulation, legislation, provision of public goods.\n- Cost-benefit analysis: Used by governments to assess whether a project's social benefits outweigh its social costs."},

    {num:16, label:"Q16: Enterprise & Economic Development",
     q:"Section B question covering enterprise, factors of production, and economic development in Ireland.",
     a:"Key concepts:\n\n- Enterprise is the factor of production that involves taking risks and organising the other factors of production.\n- The entrepreneur bears the risk of loss in return for potential profit.\n- Rewards: normal profit (minimum to keep entrepreneur in the industry) and supernormal profit (above normal profit).\n- Government supports for enterprise: grants (Enterprise Ireland, LEOs), tax incentives, training programmes.\n- FDI has been crucial for Ireland's economic development - IDA Ireland attracts multinational investment.\n- Challenges for Irish enterprise: housing costs, Brexit, global competition, climate change requirements."}
  ],

  "2024": [
    // ===== SECTION A: Short Response Questions (100 marks) =====
    {num:1, label:"Q1: Balance of Payments",
     q:"The infographic displays data relating to Ireland's Balance of Payments on the Current Account for Q2 2023.\n\n(a) From the data, calculate the balance of payments current account balance. State whether it is a surplus or a deficit. Show all workings.\n\n(b) Outline one advantage of having a surplus on the balance of payments.",
     a:"(a) Workings:\nCredits: \u20ac76bn + \u20ac91bn = \u20ac167bn\nDebits: \u20ac38bn + \u20ac83bn = \u20ac121bn\nBalance: \u20ac167bn - \u20ac121bn = \u20ac46bn SURPLUS\n\n(b) Advantages of a surplus:\n- Increased Economic Growth: If exports are greater than imports, more goods and services are being produced, which increases GNP per capita.\n- Increased Employment: If exports have increased, more people are needed to produce these goods and services.\n- Increased Tax Revenue: Exports contribute significant taxation revenue. Employment from exports generates direct tax (PAYE, USC).\n- Injection into the economy: Exports are an injection into the circular flow, increasing the multiplier effect and raising national income.\n- Attracts FDI: MNCs may become aware of Ireland's success on foreign markets and be encouraged to locate in Ireland."},

    {num:2, label:"Q2: Full Employment",
     q:"Ireland's seasonally adjusted unemployment rate for October 2023 was 4.8%. This may be regarded as full employment.\n\n(a) Explain what you understand by the term full employment.\n\nAnswer (b) or (c):\n(b) Explain, giving two reasons, why full employment is an economic aim of the government.\nOR\n(c) Explain how any other two current economic aims of the government may conflict with full employment.",
     a:"(a) Full employment is a situation when everyone in the labour force who are willing and able to work are employed at existing wage rates. In Ireland it usually occurs when the unemployment rate lies between 4% to 5%. It does not mean zero unemployment, as some frictional and structural unemployment will always exist.\n\n(b) Reasons full employment is an economic aim:\n1. Increased direct/indirect tax revenue: When individuals are in employment, they contribute through PAYE and USC (direct tax). With more disposable income, they spend more, generating VAT revenue (indirect tax).\n2. Decreased social welfare payments: If individuals are employed, the government does not have to pay social welfare, reducing current expenditure.\n3. Boosts demand/economic growth: Employed individuals have more disposable income to spend, boosting aggregate demand.\n4. Reduction in poverty: Employment provides income, increasing standard of living and reducing poverty levels.\n\n(c) Conflicts with full employment:\n1. Full employment vs Price stability: With full employment comes increased spending, which can lead to demand-pull inflation.\n2. Full employment vs Balanced budget: Government may increase expenditure to maintain full employment, conflicting with its desire to balance the budget.\n3. Full employment vs Balance of payments equilibrium: More people working means higher incomes, and as Ireland is a small open economy, some increased income will be spent on imports, potentially reducing the surplus.\n4. Full employment vs Housing for all: Full employment increases demand for home ownership, but labour shortages, planning permission difficulties, and supply lags create housing problems."},

    {num:3, label:"Q3: Price Ceiling & Energy Crisis",
     q:"During 2022, the equilibrium megawatt price per hour for electricity was \u20ac600. The European Commission considered a \u20ac200 per megawatt hour limit.\n\n(a) Illustrate on the diagram how this proposal would alter the market.\n\nAnswer (b) or (c):\n(b) Explain your understanding of the economic term price ceiling.\nOR\n(c) In Budget 2024 the government announced energy credits of \u20ac450 for all households. Explain why the government introduced this credit.",
     a:"(a) On the diagram, draw a horizontal line at \u20ac200 (below the equilibrium price of \u20ac600). This creates excess demand as the quantity demanded at \u20ac200 exceeds the quantity supplied. Label the price ceiling line at P1 (\u20ac200) and show the gap between quantity demanded and quantity supplied as excess demand.\n\n(b) A price ceiling is a maximum price, usually set by a government, that can be charged for a good/service by law. This price is set below the equilibrium price set by the market - a firm cannot legally exceed this maximum price. It is a measure put in place to prevent consumers being charged excessive prices. However, it creates excess demand (shortage) as the low price discourages supply but encourages demand.\n\n(c) Reasons for \u20ac450 energy credit:\n- Ease cost of living / improve standard of living: The main aim was to reduce electricity bills for all households as inflation was still very high, negatively impacting citizens' standards of living.\n- Protect fixed income holders: The \u20ac450 intervention helped those on fixed incomes who saw a big drop in living standards as energy costs soared in 2022/2023.\n- Market Failure: This intervention helped protect consumers suffering from a partial market failure (the market produced an unsatisfactory price).\n- War in Ukraine: This \u20ac450 intervention (costing over \u20ac1.2 billion) was part of a broader \u20ac4.1 billion package supporting households and businesses during high energy prices caused by Russia's invasion of Ukraine."},

    {num:4, label:"Q4: Capital Deepening & Demand for Labour",
     q:"(a) The table shows a firm's capital to labour ratio:\n2022: 5 machines, 5 workers (ratio 1:1)\n2023: 10 machines, 5 workers (ratio 2:1)\nTick whether the firm has engaged in capital widening or capital deepening. Explain.\n\nAnswer (b) or (c):\n(b) Outline two factors which may affect an individual company's demand for labour.\nOR\n(c) Explain the term Marginal Efficiency of Capital (MEC).",
     a:"(a) The firm has engaged in CAPITAL DEEPENING.\nCapital deepening occurs when an increase in the capital stock leads to more capital per worker. In 2023, the firm is employing 2 machines per worker compared to 2022 when it was only employing 1 machine per worker. The number of workers stayed the same (5) but machines doubled (from 5 to 10).\n\n(Capital widening would mean the capital-to-labour ratio stays the same while both increase proportionally.)\n\n(b) Factors affecting demand for labour:\n1. Wage Rate: The lower the wage rate, the higher the firm's demand for labour. If wage rate increases, cost to employer increases, which may lower demand.\n2. Demand for the firm's output (derived demand): If demand for a firm's output is high, it may hire extra staff. During recessions, demand for labour falls.\n3. Availability of new technology: New technology can lead to a fall in demand for labour (e.g. self-service checkouts, online check-in facilities).\n4. Entrepreneurs' expectations: If optimistic about the future, they may invest in new projects generating demand for labour.\n5. Price of other factors: A firm compares the cost of capital with labour to determine which is more competitive.\n6. Government incentives/subsidies: e.g. reducing employer's PRSI or LEO employment grants.\n7. MRP of labour: Will the worker generate more revenue than his/her wage rate? If so, it is profitable to employ them.\n\n(c) The Marginal Efficiency of Capital (MEC) is the extra profit earned as a result of employing one extra unit of capital. It measures the expected rate of return on an additional unit of investment."},

    {num:5, label:"Q5: Excess Demand & Concert Tickets",
     q:"Harry Styles performed a concert at Slane Castle on 10th June 2023 with a maximum capacity of 80,000 people. Ticket prices were \u20ac97.10 each and the concert sold out in hours.\n\n(a) Using the information, illustrate with a fully labelled diagram how a shortage of tickets may arise.\n\n(b) Explain your diagram.",
     a:"(a) Diagram should show:\n- Price on Y-axis, Quantity on X-axis\n- Vertical supply curve (perfectly inelastic) at 80,000 tickets\n- Downward-sloping demand curve\n- Price line at \u20ac97.10 below the equilibrium price\n- Excess demand shown as the gap between quantity demanded and 80,000 at the price of \u20ac97.10\n\n(b) Explanation:\nThe demand for tickets is downward sloping from left to right (law of demand). The supply of tickets is fixed/perfectly inelastic at 80,000 (the venue's maximum capacity cannot be changed regardless of price). If the price of tickets (\u20ac97.10) is set below the equilibrium price, there will be excess demand - more people want to buy tickets at that price than there are tickets available. This is why the concert sold out in hours, with many potential buyers unable to get tickets."},

    {num:6, label:"Q6: Cost Curves (AC & MC)",
     q:"(a) With the aid of a fully labelled diagram (including the axes), explain the relationship between a firm's short run average cost curve and its marginal cost curve.\n\n(b) Explain the shape of the short run average cost curve (downward sloping part and upward sloping part).",
     a:"(a) Diagram: U-shaped Average Cost (AC) curve and MC curve. MC intersects AC at the minimum point of AC. Y-axis: Cost/Price/\u20ac, X-axis: Quantity/Output.\n\nRelationship:\n- If marginal cost is less than average cost, then average cost is falling.\n- If marginal cost is greater than average cost, then average cost is rising.\n- If marginal cost equals average cost, then average cost is at its minimum point (constant).\n\n(b) Shape of the short run AC curve:\n\nDownward sloping part:\nSpecialisation/division of labour: As production increases, the firm can employ specialists or existing workers can concentrate on fewer tasks. This leads to greater efficiency and lower unit costs.\nOR: Greater spread of fixed costs: As output increases, fixed costs are spread over a larger number of units. Fixed costs don't increase directly with production, so the fixed cost per unit falls.\n\nUpward sloping part:\nThe law of diminishing marginal returns: As more of a variable factor (labour) is added to a fixed factor (capital), at some stage the increase in output caused by the last unit of the variable factor will begin to decline. It takes more workers to produce each additional unit of output, so average costs begin to rise."},

    {num:7, label:"Q7: Market Failure (Vaping)",
     q:"The number of teenagers in Ireland who vape is on the rise. Vaping poses a number of possible dangers to teenagers.\n\n(a) Explain why the purchase of vape products are a form of market failure.\n\n(b) Outline two ways the Irish government could intervene in the vaping market to overcome this market failure.",
     a:"(a) The purchase of demerit goods such as vape products is regarded as market failure because in a free market, vapes will be overproduced and overconsumed. Their consumption causes negative externalities - effects on third parties not involved in the consumption or production of vape products. Vape products are demerit goods as users may underestimate or be unaware of their harmful effects. Their free-market price fails to reflect their true private and social cost. If the free market took full account of the private and social costs of vapes, their price would be much higher.\n\n(b) Government interventions:\n1. Ban sale of vapes to those under 18 years of age: The government could ban the sale of vapes to consumers under 18 and enforce this law by imposing heavier penalties for sellers who breach the law.\n2. Impose indirect taxes/excise duties on vape products: This would increase the price, reducing demand (especially among price-sensitive teenagers). The tax revenue could fund public health campaigns.\n3. Regulation and advertising restrictions: Ban advertising and marketing of vape products, especially those targeted at young people.\n4. Education/information campaigns: Provide information about the health dangers of vaping to discourage consumption."},

    {num:8, label:"Q8: Price Discrimination",
     q:"Price discrimination remains a popular pricing strategy used by firms worldwide.\n\n(a) Explain, using an example, what you understand by the term price discrimination.\n\n(b) Outline two characteristics of consumers that permit/allow price discrimination to take place.",
     a:"(a) Price discrimination occurs when a firm charges different prices to different consumers for the same good or service, where the price difference is not due to differences in costs of production. Example: A cinema charging adults \u20ac12 for a ticket but charging students \u20ac8 for the same film, same seat, same screening. The cost to the cinema of providing the service is the same for both consumers.\n\n(b) Consumer characteristics that permit price discrimination:\n1. Consumer ignorance: The consumer is unaware that different prices are being charged to different groups. They don't know they could potentially get the product cheaper.\n2. Consumer indifference: Consumers are aware that price discrimination exists but they don't care enough to seek out the cheaper price. The convenience of purchasing at the higher price outweighs the saving.\n3. Different price elasticities of demand: Different groups of consumers have different sensitivities to price changes. Students and pensioners tend to be more price elastic (responsive to price changes) while business travellers tend to be price inelastic.\n4. Consumer attitudes: Some consumers feel the product is worth paying more for rather than going without it."},

    {num:9, label:"Q9: Opportunity Cost & Externalities",
     q:"(a) Coillte has pledged to add 100,000 hectares of woodland to the 440,000 hectares it already manages by 2050, costing \u20ac2 billion.\nOutline one opportunity cost of this pledge and one social benefit.\n\n(b) The Atlantic Technological University was launched in April 2022, creating a positive externality for counties Donegal, Sligo, and Mayo.\nExplain what you understand by the term positive externality.",
     a:"(a) Opportunity cost: The \u20ac2 billion spent on woodland expansion could have been used for alternative purposes such as investment in social housing, healthcare infrastructure, or road improvements. The opportunity cost is the next best alternative forgone.\n\nSocial benefit: Increased woodland helps combat climate change by absorbing carbon dioxide from the atmosphere (carbon sequestration). Other social benefits include biodiversity, recreational amenities, flood prevention, and improved air quality for the wider community.\n\n(b) A positive externality is a benefit that is enjoyed by a third party who is not directly involved in the production or consumption of a good or service. The third party did not pay for this benefit. In the case of ATU, the university creates benefits for the wider community beyond just the students and staff - local businesses benefit from increased spending, the region benefits from a more educated workforce, and communities benefit from research and cultural activities the university provides."},

    {num:10, label:"Q10: National Income Accounts (GDP to GNI)",
     q:"Given that GDP at Current Market Prices was \u20ac430bn, use the information to calculate GNI at CMP.\nData: Net Factor Income from Abroad: -\u20ac105bn; EU Subsidies: \u20ac2bn; EU Taxes: \u20ac0.5bn.\n\n(i) GNP at CMP = \u20ac325bn (given)\n(ii) Calculate GNI at CMP.\n\n(b) Explain the term Net Factor Income from Abroad.",
     a:"(i) GNP at CMP = GDP at CMP + Net Factor Income from Abroad\n= \u20ac430bn + (-\u20ac105bn) = \u20ac325bn (given)\n\n(ii) GNI at CMP = GNP at CMP + EU Subsidies - EU Taxes\n= \u20ac325bn + \u20ac2bn - \u20ac0.5bn\n= \u20ac326.5bn\n\n(b) Net Factor Income from Abroad (NFIA) is the difference between income earned by Irish residents/companies from their economic activities abroad, and income earned by foreign residents/companies from their economic activities in Ireland.\n\nIreland's NFIA is negative (-\u20ac105bn) because large amounts of profit earned by multinational corporations operating in Ireland are repatriated to their home countries. The outflow of profits from Ireland exceeds the inflow of income earned by Irish people/companies abroad. This is why Ireland's GNP is significantly lower than its GDP."},

    // ===== SECTION B: Extended Response Questions (300 marks) =====
    {num:11, label:"Q11: Tourism, Multiplier & Market Equilibrium",
     q:"(a)(i) Calculate the percentage increase in foreign tourists in August 2023 (737,600) compared to July 2021 (380,000). Show workings.\n(ii) Outline the effect of this increase in tourism on Ireland's circular flow of income.\n(iii) Outline one possible disadvantage of increasing tourism numbers.\n\n(b)(i) Given MPT = 0.22, MPM = 0.30, MPC = 0.6, calculate the multiplier and explain its economic meaning.\n(ii) Explain how a reduction in income tax rates would affect the multiplier.\n(iii) Outline two uses of national income statistics.\n\n(c) Assume the market for Irish organic ice cream is in equilibrium. Explain, with diagrams, the effects of:\n(i) A prolonged heatwave during summer.\n(ii) An increase in lactose intolerant consumers.\n(iii) Producers receiving a subsidy for organic ice cream production.",
     a:"(a)(i) Percentage increase = ((737,600 - 380,000) / 380,000) x 100\n= (357,600 / 380,000) x 100 = 94.1% increase\n\n(ii) Tourism spending by foreign visitors is an injection into Ireland's circular flow of income (similar to exports). It increases the flow of money in the economy, leading to a multiplier effect as the tourism spending circulates through various sectors (hotels, restaurants, transport, retail).\n\n(iii) Disadvantage of increasing tourism:\n- Increased pressure on infrastructure and housing: tourist hotspots may experience overcrowding, strain on public services, and increased property prices/rents as homes are converted to short-term holiday lets (e.g. Airbnb), reducing housing supply for residents.\n\n(b)(i) Multiplier = 1 / (MPT + MPM + MPS)\nFirst calculate MPS: MPC + MPS + MPT + MPM = 1\nMPS = 1 - 0.6 - 0.22 - 0.30 = -0.12\nOR using: Multiplier = 1 / (1 - MPC) if only domestic factors considered\nMore accurately: Multiplier = 1 / (MPT + MPM + MPS)\nSince MPC = 0.6, we can derive MPS = 1 - MPC - MPT - MPM = 1 - 0.6 - 0.22 - 0.30 = -0.12\nUsing the withdrawal method: K = 1 / (1 - MPC + MPT + MPM)\n= 1 / (1 - 0.6 + 0.22 + 0.30) = 1 / (0.4 + 0.22 + 0.30) = 1 / 0.92 = 1.09\n\nOR: K = 1 / (1 - MPC) is simplified to K = 1 / 0.4 = 2.5\n\nEconomic meaning: For every \u20ac1 injected into the economy, national income will ultimately increase by the multiplier value. The initial spending circulates through the economy as one person's spending becomes another's income.\n\n(ii) A reduction in income tax rates would increase the multiplier. Lower taxes mean consumers have more disposable income (higher MPC), so more of each euro earned is respent in the economy rather than being withdrawn as tax. The MPT (marginal propensity to tax) falls, reducing total withdrawals and increasing the multiplier.\n\n(iii) Uses of national income statistics:\n1. Comparing living standards between countries: GDP/GNP per capita allows comparison of average living standards across different nations.\n2. Measuring economic growth: Comparing national income figures over time shows whether the economy is growing or contracting, helping government plan economic policy.\n\n(c)(i) Prolonged heatwave:\nDemand shifts RIGHT from D to D1. A heatwave increases the desire for ice cream, increasing demand at every price level. Equilibrium price rises from Pe to Pe1 and equilibrium quantity increases from Qe to Qe1.\n\n(ii) Increase in lactose intolerant consumers:\nDemand shifts LEFT from D to D1. More lactose intolerant consumers means fewer people willing/able to buy dairy ice cream, decreasing demand. Equilibrium price falls from Pe to Pe1 and equilibrium quantity decreases from Qe to Qe1.\n\n(iii) Producers receiving a subsidy:\nSupply shifts RIGHT from S to S1. A subsidy reduces producers' costs of production, allowing them to supply more at every price level. Equilibrium price falls from Pe to Pe1 and equilibrium quantity increases from Qe to Qe1. Consumers benefit from lower prices and greater availability."},

    {num:12, label:"Q12: Taxation, Inflation & Regulation",
     q:"(a)(i) Explain two canons/principles of taxation (other than certainty).\n(ii) Outline two effects of an increase in hidden economy activities.\n(iii) A new 30% tax rate for middle-income earners has been proposed. Outline one economic consequence for either the taxpayer or the government.\n\n(b)(i) Outline the overall trend of the CPI annual % change from March to October 2023.\n(ii) Calculate the price index for the current year given weights (Food 65%, Transport 20%, Other 15%) and prices.\n(iii) Outline two possible economic effects of high price inflation.\n\n(c)(i) Outline two reasons why the gambling industry should be regulated.\n(ii) Outline one possible effect of demerit good markets.\n(iii) One assumption of perfect competition is perfect knowledge. Explain how imperfect knowledge can lead to market failure.",
     a:"(a)(i) Canons of taxation:\n1. Equity: The tax system should operate fairly. Those with greater ability to pay should contribute proportionally more (progressive taxation). The burden should not fall disproportionately on lower earners.\n2. Economy: The cost of collecting the tax should be far less than the revenue generated. An efficient tax system minimises administrative costs while maximising revenue collection.\n3. Convenience: Tax should be levied at a time and in a manner most convenient for the taxpayer (e.g. PAYE deducted at source from wages).\n4. Should not act as a disincentive: Tax should not discourage people from working, saving, or investing.\n\n(ii) Effects of increased hidden economy:\n1. Loss of tax revenue: Income from hidden economic activities is not declared, reducing the government's tax take and its ability to fund public services.\n2. Inaccurate national income statistics: Hidden economic activity is not recorded in official GDP/GNP figures, making economic data unreliable for policy planning.\n3. Unfair competition: Businesses operating in the hidden economy avoid taxes and regulations, giving them an unfair advantage over legitimate businesses.\n\n(iii) Economic consequence of a new 30% rate:\nFor the taxpayer: Increased disposable income - middle-income earners would pay 30% instead of 40% on a portion of their income, leaving them with more take-home pay to spend or save.\nFor the government: Reduced tax revenue in the short term - the lower rate would mean less income tax collected from middle earners, potentially creating a budget shortfall.\n\n(b)(i) The CPI annual % change shows a downward trend from March to October 2023. Inflation was at its highest around March (approximately 7%) and declined steadily to approximately 3.6% by October. This indicates that while prices are still rising, the rate of increase is slowing (disinflation).\n\n(ii) Price index calculation:\nFood: Simple price index = (66/60) x 100 = 110. Weight result = 110 x 0.65 = 71.5\nTransport: Simple price index = (45/30) x 100 = 150. Weight result = 150 x 0.20 = 30.0\nOther: Simple price index = (96/80) x 100 = 120. Weight result = 120 x 0.15 = 18.0\nPrice Index = 71.5 + 30.0 + 18.0 = 119.5\nThis means the general price level has increased by 19.5% from the base year.\n\n(iii) Economic effects of high inflation:\n1. Reduced purchasing power: As prices rise, the value of money falls, and consumers can buy fewer goods and services with the same income, reducing their standard of living.\n2. Loss of international competitiveness: If Irish inflation is higher than that of trading partners, Irish exports become more expensive, reducing demand and potentially worsening the balance of payments.\n\n(c)(i) Reasons for gambling regulation:\n1. Consumer protection: Gambling can be addictive and lead to financial ruin, mental health problems, and family breakdown. Regulation protects vulnerable consumers from exploitation.\n2. Prevention of money laundering: Unregulated gambling can be used to launder proceeds of crime. Regulation ensures proper oversight and reporting of transactions.\n\n(ii) Effect of demerit good markets:\nDemerit goods (like cigarettes) are overproduced and overconsumed in a free market because consumers underestimate the private and social costs. This leads to negative externalities such as increased healthcare costs (borne by taxpayers), passive smoking affecting third parties, and reduced workforce productivity.\n\n(iii) Imperfect knowledge and market failure:\nPerfect competition assumes all buyers and sellers have perfect knowledge of prices, quality, and market conditions. In reality, imperfect knowledge means consumers may not be aware of all available options, prices, or product quality. This can lead to market failure as consumers make suboptimal choices (e.g. paying too much, buying inferior products, or consuming goods whose true costs they don't understand). Firms may also exploit information asymmetry to charge higher prices or sell inferior products."},

    {num:13, label:"Q13: Market Structures & Competition",
     q:"Section B question covering market structures (perfect competition, monopoly, oligopoly, monopolistic competition), barriers to entry, and competition policy.",
     a:"Key concepts:\n\n- Perfect competition: Many buyers and sellers, homogeneous products, perfect knowledge, free entry/exit, price-takers. Long-run equilibrium: normal profit only (P = MC = AC at minimum AC).\n\n- Monopoly: Single seller, unique product, high barriers to entry, price-maker. Can earn supernormal profit in long run. May lead to higher prices and lower output than competitive markets.\n\n- Oligopoly: Few large firms dominate, interdependent decision-making, significant barriers to entry, non-price competition (advertising, branding). Kinked demand curve theory explains price rigidity.\n\n- Monopolistic competition: Many firms, differentiated products, low barriers to entry, some price-making power. Short-run supernormal profits attracted away by new entrants in long run.\n\n- Barriers to entry: Economies of scale, legal barriers (patents, licenses), brand loyalty, high start-up costs, control of key resources.\n\n- Competition policy: Government intervention to prevent anti-competitive behaviour (price fixing, cartels, abuse of dominant position). In Ireland, the CCPC (Competition and Consumer Protection Commission) enforces competition law."},

    {num:14, label:"Q14: International Trade & Globalisation",
     q:"Section B question covering international trade, globalisation, the EU, and Ireland's trading position.",
     a:"Key concepts:\n\n- Absolute advantage: A country can produce a good more efficiently (using fewer resources) than another country.\n- Comparative advantage: A country can produce a good at a lower opportunity cost than another country. Even if one country is better at producing everything, trade is still beneficial based on comparative advantage.\n\n- Free trade benefits: Lower prices, greater consumer choice, specialisation, economies of scale, increased competition.\n- Protectionism: Tariffs, quotas, subsidies, embargoes. Arguments for: protecting infant industries, national security, preventing dumping, safeguarding employment.\n\n- Ireland and the EU: Benefits include access to Single Market (free movement of goods, services, capital, labour), EU structural funds, and political stability. Challenges include loss of monetary policy independence and compliance costs.\n\n- Brexit impact on Ireland: Trade disruption with the UK, Northern Ireland Protocol issues, potential loss of UK as a land bridge to EU markets.\n\n- Globalisation: Increased interconnectedness of economies. Benefits include FDI, technology transfer, and cultural exchange. Challenges include inequality, environmental concerns, and loss of national sovereignty."},

    {num:15, label:"Q15: Government Policy & Economic Management",
     q:"Section B question covering fiscal policy, monetary policy, supply-side policies, and government management of the Irish economy.",
     a:"Key concepts:\n\n- Fiscal policy: Government use of taxation and spending to influence the economy. Expansionary (lower taxes/higher spending to stimulate growth) vs contractionary (higher taxes/lower spending to cool overheating economy).\n\n- Monetary policy: Controlled by the ECB for all eurozone members. Tools include interest rates, open market operations, and quantitative easing. Ireland cannot independently set interest rates.\n\n- Supply-side policies: Aim to increase the productive capacity of the economy. Include investment in education/training, infrastructure, deregulation, and reducing bureaucracy.\n\n- Budget deficit vs surplus: A deficit occurs when government spending exceeds revenue. A surplus occurs when revenue exceeds spending. The national debt is the cumulative total of all past deficits.\n\n- Automatic stabilisers: Tax revenues and social welfare payments that automatically adjust with the economic cycle, helping to smooth fluctuations.\n\n- The multiplier effect: An initial change in spending leads to a proportionally larger change in national income."},

    {num:16, label:"Q16: Factors of Production & Enterprise",
     q:"Section B question covering the four factors of production (land, labour, capital, enterprise), their rewards, and their role in economic development.",
     a:"Key concepts:\n\n- Land: All natural resources. Reward is rent. Characteristics: gift of nature, no cost of production, fixed in supply (perfectly inelastic), geographically immobile, varies in quality.\n\n- Labour: All human effort (mental and physical) in production. Reward is wages. Affected by education, skills, mobility (geographical and occupational), and population trends.\n\n- Capital: Man-made aids to production (machinery, equipment, buildings). Reward is interest/profit. Capital formation occurs through saving and investment. Types: fixed capital (buildings, machinery) and working capital (raw materials, stocks).\n\n- Enterprise: Organising the other factors, decision-making, risk-bearing, and innovation. Reward is profit (normal and supernormal). The entrepreneur bears the risk of loss.\n\n- Capital widening: Increasing capital stock in proportion to labour (ratio stays same).\n- Capital deepening: Increasing capital stock relative to labour (more capital per worker).\n\n- Marginal Efficiency of Capital (MEC): The expected rate of return on an additional unit of capital investment. Investment continues as long as MEC exceeds the interest rate.\n\n- Derived demand: Factors of production are not demanded for their own sake but because of the goods/services they produce."}
  ]
};
